            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). Probably the north-west corner of the city wall.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The valley gate.—Syriac, “the west gate.” In the western wall, the modern Jaffa gate. These two towers protected the most exposed points of the capital.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The valley gate.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Syriac, “the west gate.” In the western wall, the modern Jaffa gate. These two towers protected the most exposed points of the capital.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "At the turning of the wall.—Over the angle (ha-miqçôa ̒), i.e., on the eastern side of Zion, at a bend in the wall. This tower defended both Zion and Moriah against attacks from the south-east. (Nehemiah 3:19-20; Nehemiah 3:24-25.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "At the turning of the wall.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Over the angle",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "ha-miqçôa",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " ̒)",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": ", i.e.,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " on the eastern side of Zion, at a bend in the wall. This tower defended both Zion and Moriah against attacks from the south-east. (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Nehemiah 3:19-20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Nehemiah 3:24-25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And fortified them.—Literally, made them (the gates) strong. Or rather, perhaps, he made the towers strong, i.e., put them in a posture of defence. (Comp. 2Chronicles 11:11.) The margin is wrong. Syriac, “girded (or bound) them at their corners with clamps (glîdê, i.e., κλεῖδες) of iron.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And fortified them.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "made them",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (the gates) ",
            "children": []
